<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-623-307  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 623 307.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  Nov 8 1990 v16 n23 p1(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Plesman Publications Ltd. (Canada) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fibre called the catalyst for '90s telecom. (Intercomm '90)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Fuochi, Andre.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Fiber optics will enable the development of internationalcommunication networks that will carry voice and data around theworld at the speed of light.andP;  The technological revolution willchange the way companies function and leave behind conventionalways of management, government and education.andP;  Fiber optics willbe the catalyst for the telecommunications revolution, which someanalysts predict will happen around the turn of the century.andO;International competition in the corporate world will intensifyand companies will have to adapt to survive; telecommunicationswill play an important role in corporate decentralization andrestructuring.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Trade ShowsCommunications IndustryTrendsTechnologyFiber OpticsInternational CommunicationsVoice CommunicationsData Communications.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Fibre called the catalyst for '90s telecomandM;VANCOUVER - A technological revolution is sweeping through our worldeconomies.andP;  And according to Paul Stern, chairman, president and chiefexecutive officer of Northern Telecom Ltd., it will leave conventionalapproaches to managing companies, governing countries and educating our youngas obsolete as livery stables and blacksmith shops were at the end of thecentury.andM;Speaking at the opening plenary session of the Intercomm '90 show here lastmonth, Stern suggested that &quot;we've only seen the tip of the iceberg in thetechnological changes facing us in the '90s&quot; - a world in which no man with acellular phone is an island.andM;Fibre optics is the catalyst which will continue to &quot;revolutionize modes ofcommunication in the 1990s and beyond,&quot; Stern said.andP;  &quot;Fibre optics willenable the development of international information highways carrying data,voice and video around the world at the speed of light.&quot;andM;In the same way PCs and facsimiles affected business in the 1980s, fibreoptics will influence business in the 1990s.andP;  &quot;Fibre optics will be to the21st century what electronics was to the 20th century,&quot; he commented.andM;Stern also told delegates that a major factor in moving towards globalnetworking is interoperability.andM;&quot;Governments throughout the world must ensure that information services areeasily and widely available, unaffected by legal and regulatory clutter,leaving telecom companies free to service users,&quot; he said.andM;&quot;Over time, technological innovation and customer demand for internationalnetworking will outstrip any standard which seeks to control or containcustomers' demand for open system architectures using universal standardslike synchronous optical networks (SONet) and ISDN (integrated servicesdigital network).&quot;andM;The key, Stern emphasized, lies in transforming existing voice networks intomulti-vendor, multimedia, broadband networks.andM;Other factors in globalization have been the international availability ofcapital and the evaporation of tariffs.andM;&quot;Borders are much more transparent these days, exemplified by the free tradeagreements between Canada and the U.S.andP;  and Europe in 1992 ...andP;  Even stockmarkets are beginning to experiment with the possibility of 24-hour trading,&quot;Stern said.andM;As international competition intensifies, corporations face new demands.andP;  AsStern noted: &quot;A dominant position in a single domestic market is no longersufficient to ensure corporate survival, let alone corporate success.&quot;andM;To illustrate this point, he pointed to the fact that &quot;of the originalFortune 500 companies first listed in the 1950s only 25 per cent existtoday.&quot;andM;Even more significant, he said, is that &quot;of the 1970 Fortune 500 companies,almost 200 are gone.andM;This is evidence that businesses and institutions are not very adaptable.&quot;andM;There will be a restructuring of business on a scale which the world hasnever seen before.andP;  The more decentralized corporate environments become, thegreater role telecommunications will play.andM;The '90s will also mark the transition from a narrowband to a broadbandsociety, according to speaker Samuel Willcoxon, president of ATandamp;T'sInternational Group.andM;&quot;We'll be looking at each other instead of just talking, we'll be visualizinginformation in application after application and we'll be doing it in ouroffices and perhaps our homes,&quot; he said.andO;</TEXT></DOC>